---
import ConnectorConsole from "@/components/ConnectorConsole.svelte";
import BaseLayout from "@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Connector onboarding"
  description="RevenueCat-owned account onboarding for GrowthRat. Connect Slack, CMS, Charts, GitHub, and social distribution after the interview gate passes."
>
  <section class="hero compact">
    <div class="shell">
      <p class="eyebrow">RC activation · onboarding</p>
      <h1>Connect the accounts GrowthRat operates on your behalf.</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        Same console as <a href="/sign-in" style="color: inherit; text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">sign-in</a>,
        framed for the post-interview onboarding flow. Each connector is
        explicit: missing, pending, verified, or error. Connector loss fails
        closed for side effects.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section mint">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">What you'll connect</p>
          <h2>Five connectors run the weekly loop</h2>
        </div>
        <p class="lead">
          Slack owns approvals and reports. CMS owns long-form publishing.
          GitHub owns code samples and docs PRs. Postiz owns approved social
          distribution. RevenueCat APIs own monetization truth.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="grid">
        <article class="card">
          <span class="tag">Slack</span>
          <h3 style="margin-top: 12px;">Team requests &amp; approvals</h3>
          <p>
            Plans, draft approvals, weekly reports, and stop/resume commands run
            through Slack. Reaction-based approval promotes drafts only when
            policy allows.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <span class="tag">CMS</span>
          <h3 style="margin-top: 12px;">Long-form publishing</h3>
          <p>
            Generated artifacts stay in draft mode in your CMS until a
            RevenueCat representative approves the final version.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <span class="tag">GitHub</span>
          <h3 style="margin-top: 12px;">Code samples &amp; docs PRs</h3>
          <p>
            Sample repos, docs PRs, and feedback issues are filed under a
            GrowthRat-affiliated account with audit trails on every action.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <span class="tag">Postiz</span>
          <h3 style="margin-top: 12px;">Approved social distribution</h3>
          <p>
            One approved artifact produces multiple platform-specific drafts.
            Distribution requires an idempotency key and approval state.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <span class="tag">RevenueCat</span>
          <h3 style="margin-top: 12px;">Monetization truth</h3>
          <p>
            Charts and Metrics API access lets the agent reason about
            subscription outcomes, not just behavioral funnels.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <span class="tag">DataForSEO</span>
          <h3 style="margin-top: 12px;">Demand signals</h3>
          <p>
            Keyword difficulty, intent, and SERP data feed the opportunity
            engine. Score components are inspectable per opportunity.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">Connect now</p>
          <h2>Onboarding console</h2>
        </div>
        <p class="lead">
          You'll need an authenticated RevenueCat representative session.
          Tokens are stored encrypted as connected-account records, not
          platform secrets.
        </p>
      </div>
      <ConnectorConsole client:load />
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section lavender">
    <div class="shell prose">
      <h2>Trust boundaries</h2>
      <p>
        Platform secrets (operator-owned) live in Wrangler. Connector tokens
        (RevenueCat-owned) live in encrypted connected-account records created
        by an authenticated representative. The agent cannot read connector
        secrets in plaintext and cannot operate connectors that fail
        verification.
      </p>
      <p>
        Each connector goes through one of: <code>missing</code>,
        <code>pending</code>, <code>verified</code>, <code>manual_verification</code>,
        or <code>error</code>. Connector loss must degrade reads clearly and
        fail closed for side effects.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
